You are given data for a set of heat production plants, a set of time periods, a set of thermal storage units, and a set of fuel types. Each plant has a maximum and minimum heat output per period. Each plant consumes fuel according to a consumption rate per unit of heat, and each fuel type has a total available amount. Heat selling prices vary by period. Each plant has a fuel cost per MWh of heat produced. Each storage unit has a maximum energy capacity, charge and discharge rate limits per period, a round-trip efficiency, and an operating cost per MWh of charge or discharge. Each plant has a CO2 emission rate per MWh of heat, and there is a total emission limit for the entire planning horizon. The distribution network incurs a loss fraction per period. Heat demand must be met in each period after accounting for network losses. Initial stored energy levels are given for each storage unit.

